item.title: Magical Logging in bash and zsh
item.description:
Disclaimer

So far this snippet has only been tested on OSX. It should work on any *nix with some fiddling though!

References

  • This post from Simon Coffey gave me the idea to try and log all stderr from the shell to syslog or another logging facility, not just from an individual script

  • This response on ask ubuntu shows how to capture all commands to syslog

Motivation

I recently decided it’d be fun to log all of my and my coworker’s commands and stderr from our zsh sessions. Not in an Orwellian way, but because they’re all data scientists and it’d generate a lot of cool data! Also, I’ve been experimenting with the awesome elasticsearch, logstash, and kibana stack, and what better way to test it than to fill it up with a bunch of logs!

After some intense googling, there was nothing that did exactly what I wanted.

zsh version

Add this to the bottom of your .zshrc file

precmd() { eval "$PROMPT_COMMAND" }
export PROMPT_COMMAND='RETRN_VAL=$?;logger "$(fc -l -1 | sed "s/^[ ]*[0-9]+[ ]*//" ) [$RETRN_VAL]"'
exec 2> >(tee >(logger -t $(echo $USER).stderr))

bash version

Add this to the bottom of your .bashrc file

export PROMPT_COMMAND='RETRN_VAL=$?;logger "$(history 1 | sed "s/^[ ]*[0-9]+[ ]*//" ) [$RETRN_VAL]"'
exec 2> >(tee >(logger -t $(echo $USER).stderr))

Explanation

I’ll break down the zsh version since that’s my primary shell. Zsh doesn’t have the PROMPT_COMMAND magic like bash, so the line

precmd() { eval "$PROMPT_COMMAND" }

uses zsh’s “precmd” hook to emulate the behavior.

item.title: Rank K Approximation
item.description:
Explanation

A rank k approximation of some data points is the projection of those data points onto a smaller k dimensional space

Definition

Given some $m x n$ data matrix $A$ and $n x k$ orthonormal basis $B$ with rank $k$

is a rank $k$ approximation of $A$

Example

%matplotlib inline

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
from matplotlib.patches import FancyArrowPatch
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import proj3d

import numpy as np

Some Helper Functions for Plotting in 3d

class Arrow3D(FancyArrowPatch):
    def __init__(self, xs, ys, zs, *args, **kwargs):
        FancyArrowPatch.__init__(self, (0,0), (0,0), *args, **kwargs)
        self._verts3d = xs, ys, zs

    def draw(self, renderer):
        xs3d, ys3d, zs3d = self._verts3d
        xs, ys, zs = proj3d.proj_transform(xs3d, ys3d, zs3d, renderer.M)
        self.set_positions((xs[0],ys[0]),(xs[1],ys[1]))
        FancyArrowPatch.draw(self, renderer)
        
def randrange(n, vmin, vmax):
    return (vmax-vmin)*np.random.rand(n) + vmin

3 Dimensional Test Data

N = 100
xs = randrange(N, -10, 10)
ys = randrange(N, -10, 10)
zs = randrange(N, -10, 10)
data = np.vstack([xs,ys,zs]).T
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d') 
ax.plot(xs, ys, zs, 'ro', markersize=5)

ax.set_xlabel('X Label')
ax.set_ylabel('Y Label')
ax.set_zlabel('Z Label')

# Plot Axes
x_axis = [[0,10], [0,0], [0,0]]
y_axis = [[0,0], [0,-10], [0,0]]
z_axis = [[0,0], [0,0], [0,10]]
ax.plot(*x_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)
ax.plot(*y_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)
ax.plot(*z_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)

plt.show()

<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x106d6be10>

Random 2 Dimensional Subspace

Generate a random basis using two arbitrary vectors and Gram-Schmidt orthonormalization as implemented by the $QR$ matrix decomposition

two_rand_vectors = np.random.rand(9).reshape((3,3))
q,r = np.linalg.qr(two_rand_vectors)
basis = q[:2]
scale = 10
v0 = zip(np.zeros(len(basis[0])), basis[0] * scale)
v1 = zip(np.zeros(len(basis[1])), basis[1] * scale)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d') 
ax.plot(xs, ys, zs, 'ro', markersize=5)

ax.set_xlabel('X Label')
ax.set_ylabel('Y Label')
ax.set_zlabel('Z Label')

# Plot Axes
x_axis = [[0,10], [0,0], [0,0]]
y_axis = [[0,0], [0,-10], [0,0]]
z_axis = [[0,0], [0,0], [0,10]]
ax.plot(*x_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)
ax.plot(*y_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)
ax.plot(*z_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)

a = Arrow3D(*v0, mutation_scale=20, lw=3, arrowstyle="-|>", color="b")
ax.add_artist(a)

a = Arrow3D(*v1, mutation_scale=20, lw=3, arrowstyle="-|>", color="b")
ax.add_artist(a)

plt.show()

<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x10a42e1d0>

Project Onto the Subspace

proj = np.dot(data, basis.T)
rank_k_approx = np.dot(proj, basis)
rx,ry,rz = rank_k_approx.T
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d') 
ax.plot(rx, ry, rz, 'go', markersize=5)
#ax.plot(xs, ys, zs, 'ro', markersize=5)

ax.set_xlabel('X Label')
ax.set_ylabel('Y Label')
ax.set_zlabel('Z Label')

# Plot Axes
x_axis = [[0,10], [0,0], [0,0]]
y_axis = [[0,0], [0,-10], [0,0]]
z_axis = [[0,0], [0,0], [0,10]]
ax.plot(*x_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)
ax.plot(*y_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)
ax.plot(*z_axis, color='black', alpha=0.8, lw=3)

a = Arrow3D(*v0, mutation_scale=20, lw=3, arrowstyle="-|>", color="b")
ax.add_artist(a)

a = Arrow3D(*v1, mutation_scale=20, lw=3, arrowstyle="-|>", color="b")
ax.add_artist(a)

plt.show()

<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x106e94dd0>
